        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer320422624" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13746273406464335884"><u>Detonating Daughter, Disintegrated Marriage</u><br/><br/><i>
  <b>&quot;A forty-fifth reunion is not the best place to come looking for ass.&quot;</b>
</i><br/><br/>The most popular guy in Newark&apos;s Weequahic High School Class of 1945, Seymour &quot;Swede&quot; Levov, who was the school&apos;s star athlete in 3 sports, was called Swede due to his blonde hair, blue eyes and Nordic looks. He was the elder son of a successful Jewish American glove manufacturer. He eventually takes over dad&apos;s glove factory and marries the Miss New Jersey 1949, an Irish Catholic </span>
  <span id="freeText13746273406464335884" style="display:none"><u>Detonating Daughter, Disintegrated Marriage</u><br /><br /><i>
  <b>"A forty-fifth reunion is not the best place to come looking for ass."</b>
</i><br /><br />The most popular guy in Newark's Weequahic High School Class of 1945, Seymour "Swede" Levov, who was the school's star athlete in 3 sports, was called Swede due to his blonde hair, blue eyes and Nordic looks. He was the elder son of a successful Jewish American glove manufacturer. He eventually takes over dad's glove factory and marries the Miss New Jersey 1949, an Irish Catholic girl from nearby Elizabeth. He has set up, he believes, the perfect American life in a big house in an idyllic town with a gorgeous wife and a cute daughter. <br /><br />Yet, as the Vietnam War and racial unrest plague the country, his daughter, Merry, who has a severe stuttering problem, becomes irate at the U.S. military involvement in Vietnam, and grows increasingly erratic and hideously overweight. In 1968, at 41, Swede's <i>American Pastoral</i> life is blasted to smithereens when Merry, then only 16, bombs the local post office in protest against American intervention in Vietnam, and goes permanently into hiding. He doesn't see her for 5 years, finding her in inner city Newark, at 21 years old, emaciated and awfully kept. The story primarily relates to the 5 years between the bombing and this meeting and it culminates in a 1973 dinner party with guests from local social circles and results in another explosion in Swede's life, figuratively speaking, nearly as big as the one in 1968. The rest of the story is spoiler material.<br /><br />The novel confronts the American social and political turmoil of the late 1960s and early 1970s (which the novel describes as a manifestation of the "<i>indigenous American berserk</i>"), in the form of riots, race problems, protests, bombings, the sexual revolution, the Watergate scandal and <i>Deep Throat</i> (both the Watergate source and the 1972 porno flick).<br /><br />I recommend this book if you liked any of Roth's other novels (this one's easier to swallow as realistic than a few of his others) or have any interest in the tumultuous era.<br /><br /><i>Weather Underground</i> Motto, quoted in <i>American Pastoral</i> <blockquote>"<i><b>We are against everything that is good and decent in honky America</b>. We will <b>loot</b> and <b>burn</b> and <b>destroy</b>. <b>We are the incubation of your mothers' nightmares</b></i>." </blockquote> *4.4 stars*<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="13746273406464335884" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
