  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1278082505" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1278082505" />
    <a title="Chrissie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/632247-chrissie"><img alt="Chrissie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1321799585p2/632247.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1278082505?book_show_action=true">Mar 28, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chrissie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chrissie" href="/user/show/632247-chrissie">Chrissie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=usa">usa</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=relationships">relationships</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=2018-read">2018-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=humor">humor</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=returned">returned</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=religion">religion</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=audible-uk">audible-uk</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=hf">hf</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1278082505" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15569955652114626779">The central theme of this book concerns a father’s love for his daughter who commits a reprehensible deed, a misdeed that is scarcely forgivable. That one misdeed becomes several. The daughter, Merry, <a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[kills four people <a class='jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction'>(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>, with full cognizance and intent. The deeds are planned. The relationship between the daughter and her parents disintegrates totally. Who is responsible? Any parent would ask this.<br/><br/>The father, Seymour Levov, nicknamed the “Swede”, is tall, blond and h</span>
  <span id="freeText15569955652114626779" style="display:none">The central theme of this book concerns a father’s love for his daughter who commits a reprehensible deed, a misdeed that is scarcely forgivable. That one misdeed becomes several. The daughter, Merry, <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[kills four people <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>, with full cognizance and intent. The deeds are planned. The relationship between the daughter and her parents disintegrates totally. Who is responsible? Any parent would ask this.<br /><br />The father, Seymour Levov, nicknamed the “Swede”, is tall, blond and handsome. In high school he was championed, the school’s best athlete and highly admired. Now, with his father, the two run the family’s glove-making business with factories in Newark, Puerto Rico and for a time also in Czechoslovakia. Seymour loves his daughter. He adores her; the love he feels for her and the memories he has of her childhood are poignantly drawn. Then, as a teenager, she rebels, veering off in a direction contrary to all the basic principles by which she has been raised. How does a parent balance the deep-seated love felt for one’s child if as an adult they behave in a contradictory manner? Such a situation would be a nightmare to any parent. This is the book’s central theme. This theme is movingly and insightfully portrayed. The dialogs between parent and child are pitch-perfect; the words capture with stunning accuracy how teenagers and parents communicate and illustrate how diametrically opposed views can become. This is the aspect of the book I like. <br /><br />However, the book goes further; infidelity and adulterous behavior of the adults is added to the mix. That which begins as a promising focal point becomes diluted. The focus morphs into a statement about the fallibility and deviant behavior of people in general. The story becomes too long, too drawn out, too unwieldly. It turns into an exaggerated and negative philosophical discourse.<br /><br />The story is set in New Jersey during the late 1960s and early 1970s. The Newark Riots, the Vietnam War, Watergate and the Weathermen (WUO) set the background for the events. In this sense, the book can be classified as historical fiction. Political dissent and the view that the grounding principles structuring society seemed to be crumbling characterize the era and the book.<br /><br />In 1985, Seymour asks Nathan Zuckerman, an author who had been his younger brother’s childhood friend, to write about the family. Then in 1995, the author and Seymour’s younger brother meet at their forty-fifth high school reunion. Nathan Zuckerman learns that Seymour had recently died of prostate cancer. Zuckerman then reconstructs the events of Seymour’s life on the basis of newspaper articles, his own impressions of the high school hero as he remembers him from his youth, talks with Seymour’s brother and with Seymour before his death. Zuckerman astutely reconstructs Seymour’s emotions and thoughts, as well as the relationship between mother and daughter. Both are well done.<br /><br />So what I like about this book is the accurate portrayal of teenagers’ rebellion against parents. The path toward independence and adulthood is not easy for either part. Both see the others’ views with complete incomprehension.<br /><br />I dislike both how sex is drawn and how it is woven into the story. It takes too prominent a role in the events and is too often portrayed in an excessively vulgar manner. Perhaps the author meant to titillate the reading public? The author makes sex dirty.<br /><br />As mentioned, the family is in the glove-making business. You will learn all the intricacies of the trade and how a glove should be made if it is to be made properly. Which leathers are best, how the leather should be stretched and sewn and dried and stored; every detail imaginable is here! This is interesting, for a while, but then it goes on too long. Throughout the entire book, details about people and places and happenings get off track; the book should have been tightened. <br /><br />The audiobook I listened to is narrated by Ron Silver. In conversations where different characters are speaking to each other, they all sound exactly the same! It is impossible to hear who is talking! Seymour has a very particular way of speaking; he has a Jewish East Coast accent. This the narrator does well, but not all the characters should sound as he does. Even Seymour and Merry sound the same, except that Merry stutters. The stuttering is very well performed by the narrator. I have given the narration three stars.<br /><br />Although I like the way the parent / daughter relationship is drawn, the book becomes unwieldy and is way too long. The philosophical message imparted is exaggerated and totally unnecessary. For me, the book as a whole was merely OK.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15569955652114626779" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

