    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1406674695" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1406674695" />
    <a title="Steven Godin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/26706841-steven-godin"><img alt="Steven Godin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1621019440p2/26706841.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1406674695?book_show_action=true">Oct 02, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Steven Godin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Steven Godin" href="/user/show/26706841-steven-godin">Steven Godin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/26706841-steven-godin?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/26706841-steven-godin?shelf=america-canada">america-canada</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1406674695" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9613267705035769711">I hold Philip Roth in quite high regards and would liken him to a bottle of vintage fine wine, his books might not be the most exciting page turners in the world but they are deep, thoughtful, intelligent and slow burning(a retired history professor reading a Roth novel with a cuban cigar and a swig of brandy comes to mind!), and although from what I have read of his work so far this would be my least favourite it&apos;s not the sinking ship that others have made it out to be, yes at times it was bor</span>
  <span id="freeText9613267705035769711" style="display:none">I hold Philip Roth in quite high regards and would liken him to a bottle of vintage fine wine, his books might not be the most exciting page turners in the world but they are deep, thoughtful, intelligent and slow burning(a retired history professor reading a Roth novel with a cuban cigar and a swig of brandy comes to mind!), and although from what I have read of his work so far this would be my least favourite it's not the sinking ship that others have made it out to be, yes at times it was boring and probably far too long but if I had to use one word that would be 'frustrating' as for every twenty or so pages would be worthy of my time the next twenty would not, I mean do I really need to know the manufacturing process of ladies gloves in such a way that you just want to skip a page or two.Thankfully the last third made up for the disappointing first two thirds and in the end I was left feeling a bit in awe.<br /><br />The Main story running throughout is of Seymour Levov (or the Swede as he is referred to)and trying to understand why his beloved Daughter Merry turned from an all american child into a raging and hateful teenager who carries out an act of terrorism on their community that rocks the family to it's core. Roth is clearly passionate about his country and there are underlying themes of family loyalty, civil disobedience and trouble brewing during the Lyndon Johnson era and the Vietnam war where so many young Americans became disillusioned. There is a lot of flashback involved which helps to understand the family history and I really felt a deep sorrow for Merry during the moment when her father finds her years later after she flees home. I appreciated reading this more than actually enjoying it and it does have flaws but it's deeply compassionate, intelligent and slightly sad, as for the pulitzer prize I have mixed feelings. <br /> </span>
  <a data-text-id="9613267705035769711" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

